Here, we demonstrate a pathway to minimise non-radiative voltage losses in an OPV device without penalizing EQE. We introduce a bulk heterojunction (BHJ) solar cell based on polymer:NFA26 blends that combine relatively high power conversion efficiency (PCE > 12%) with high EQEEL (10−4) and low non-radiative loss ΔVOC,nr=0.24V\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta {{V}}_{{{OC}},{{nr}}} = 0.24\,{\mathrm{V}}$$\end{document}. We employ femtosecond transient absorption (TA) spectroscopy, coupled to a global analysis technique, to unravel the kinetics of electron and hole transfer, in addition to charge separation, in the blend. We gain further insight into the electronic structure of the interfacial CT state through quantum chemical calculations, which we apply to model the population equilibrium between interfacial and bulk states from EL and EQE spectra. We show that this equilibrium is decisively controlled by the degeneracy and energy of the interfacial CT states and that it attains a near-optimum value in WF3:O-IDTBR, explaining its ability to produce a high open-circuit voltage (VOC) and EQE at the same time. We generalise these results by showing that, for any blend with a low driving force, there exists an optimum CT energy, which is at the crossing point of normalised VOC and EQE curves along the CT energy axis. We discuss known methods to adjust the CT energy in a given blend in light of this new functional relationship.

